com.locuslabs.sdk.internal.maps.controller

Class MapViewController

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.locuslabs.sdk.internal.maps.view.ViewController
      • com.locuslabs.sdk.internal.maps.view.TypedViewController<MapView>
        • com.locuslabs.sdk.internal.maps.controller.MapViewController

  • public final class MapViewController
extends TypedViewController<MapView>
    Main entry point for all view controllers. This view controller essentially corresponds to the main map screen. There are separate view controllers for each functional area of the user interface. Whenever one view controllers needs to talk to another view controller, it should ask the MapViewController for a pointer to the other view controller, e.g. getNavigationInputViewController().

    All other view controllers are intended to be declared package-private, and only this view controller is intended to be declared public.

      • floorIdChanged

        public void floorIdChanged(java.lang.String newFloorId)
        This function is called from the Core JS-SDK via Java's Reflection.

        The link is established with the following call in MapViewController(MapView, JavaScriptEnvironment, DefaultMap, JavaScriptMap, JavaScriptMapView, Venue):

        this.javaScriptMap.addChangeEventListener( "floorId_changed", this, "floorIdChanged" );

        Parameters:
        newFloorId - the id of the new floor

      • showMyLocationButton

        public void showMyLocationButton()
        Show the My Location button. By default it is View.GONE. Once changed to View.VISIBLE, it remains visible until the user closes the map. Once visible, the icon can change, for example if positioning is lost (by onPositionChanged() receiving a null position), then the icon will be set to Unavailable.

        Initializes the state to Out-of-Range but that should be quickly changed as soon as the map gets recentered to current location (see setupMyLocationButton(ImageView, TextView) use of MapView.OnCenterPositionChangedListener)

        Calls SearchViewController.showMyLocationButton() and NavigationViewController.showMyLocationButton()

      • setMyLocationAvailable

        public void setMyLocationAvailable()
        Sets My Location button image to a solid black dot. This tells the user that we know their location and the map is centered on that location.

        Calls SearchViewController.setMyLocationAvailable() and NavigationViewController.setMyLocationAvailable()

      • setMyLocationUnavailable

        public void setMyLocationUnavailable()
        Sets My Location button image to a line through it. This tells the user that they have walked out of range of any beacons so we don't know their location.

        Calls SearchViewController.setMyLocationUnavailable() and NavigationViewController.setMyLocationUnavailable()

      • setMyLocationOutOfRange

        public void setMyLocationOutOfRange()
        Sets My Location button image to a solid orange dot. This tells the user that we know their location but the user must have panned the map away from that location (e.g. to explore their surrounding area).

        Calls SearchViewController.setMyLocationOutOfRange() and NavigationViewController.setMyLocationOutOfRange()
